rve as references and prerequisites for the more advanced and domain-specific content in the ","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"ofamKAaGpF"},{"type":"link","url":"https://cookbooks.projectpythia.org","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Pythia Cookbook Gallery","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"Qu7Xo9MYol"}],"urlSource":"https://cookbooks.projectpythia.org","key":"NX4iv7Jol4"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"EB8ToK5jyT"}],"key":"eMniSYrgsn"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"What’s included","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"fxLgw8yst1"}],"identifier":"whats-included","label":"What’s included","html_id":"whats-included","implicit":true,"key":"RTNGBhEHA4"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The Scientific Python Ecosystem (","key":"i8C2Y0vwfT"},{"type":"abbreviation","title":"Scientific Python Ecosystem","children":[{"type":"text","value":"SPE","key":"L2wcJGGXy0"}],"key":"FSj1t2HVN7"},{"type":"text","value":") is a collection of\nopen source Python packages that support analysis, manipulation,\nand visualization of scientific data. While Project Pythia is focused\non the geoscience communities, the material contained in Pythia\nFoundations applies broadly, and may be useful to scientists, or\naspiring scientists, working in any number of disciplines. Pythia\nFoundations makes very few assumptions about the experience level\nof the reader other than having a background in math or science,\nand being comfortable using a computer, including the command line\nterminal (i.e., the ","key":"iqnEy0mkw1"},{"type":"link","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_shell","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Unix shell","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"nko5ZdclHn"}],"urlSource":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_shell","data":{"page":"Unix_shell","wiki":"https://en.wikipedia.org/","lang":"en"},"internal":false,"protocol":"wiki","key":"GevoEFQBPK"},{"type":"text","value":").\nPrior programming experience is not required.","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"CAKSOpKBhG"}],"key":"w9VkIDDfps"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Lastly, in addition to the Python language and a number of fundamental\nscientific Python packages, Pythia Foundations covers two topics\nthat we believe are essential\nto effectively using the ","key":"Q2yuUXCcXY"},{"type":"abbreviation","title":"Scientific Python Ecosystem","children":[{"type":"text","value":"SPE","key":"W7iOtz8HZO"}],"key":"FbdL6qHNh3"},{"type":"text","value":": GitHub, for sharing workflows and\nmanaging code; and Jupyter Notebooks, the technology by which all\nPythia Foundations material is presented and which is quickly\nbecoming a standard format for scientific communication of computational\nresults.","key":"KKRkbj6HJA"}],"key":"tVDB360gd2"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Organization of Pythia Foundations","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"OdEsA7asDK"}],"identifier":"organization-of-pythia-foundations","label":"Organization of Pythia Foundations","html_id":"organization-of-pythia-foundations","implicit":true,"key":"UKk2XSAdtY"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":32,"column":1},"end":{"line":41,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Pythia Foundations is organized into two main sections as seen in\nthe sidebar on the left and the schematic below: Foundational Skills, and Core Scientific\nPython Packages. The first, Foundational Skills, covers essential\nmaterial that all users of Project Pythia are expected to feel\ncomfortable with in order to make the most of the rest of the Project\nPythia content. The second, Core Scientific Python Packages, covers\nwhat we believe are the most important and fundamental packages\nin the Scientific Python Ecosystem. These packages serve as the\nbuilding blocks for many of the more geoscience focused components\nof the Scientific Python Ecosystem.","position":{"start":{"line":32,"column":1},"end":{"line":32,"column":1}},"key":"Ttc2EsLmX7"}],"key":"Q2wivRLb4u"},{"type":"image","url":"/_preview/582/build/ProjectPythia_Founda-5a631af8397e1ba5ae60a7b958ce795b.jpg","alt":"Foundations Infographic","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"xmMNsrTdSE","urlSource":"../images/ProjectPythia_Foundations_Infographic_v4.jpg"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Running Pythia Foundations examples","position":{"start":{"line":45,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"key":"E4HeXdM6Dm"}],"identifier":"running-pythia-foundations-examples","label":"Running Pythia Foundations examples","html_id":"running-pythia-foundations-examples","implicit":true,"key":"VhPb3Z3bqr"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":61,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"All of the content in Pythia Foundations is authored in Markdown\nand presented in the form of ","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"JbKHj6YpQn"},{"type":"link","url":"https://jupyter.org","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Jupyter\nNotebook","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"b8oWYkgn65"}],"urlSource":"https://jupyter.org","key":"QutZ5wr1Sh"},{"type":"text","value":" “chapters”. The power\nof Jupyter Notebooks is that they can contain both static text and\nexecutable code that you can interact with. When you navigate to a\nbook chapter such as ","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"Hv7bPOIsYX"},{"type":"link","url":"/core/matplotlib/matplotlib-basics","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Matplotlib\nBasics","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"j3lbhndDBu"}],"urlSource":"../core/matplotlib/matplotlib-basics","dataUrl":"/core.matplotlib.matplotlib-basics.json","internal":true,"protocol":"file","key":"RyoERNgAUq"},{"type":"text","value":"\nyou will see static text, Python code, and the rendered output of\nthat code in the form of the many figures that appear. In the case\nof Matplotlib Basics these figures are produced by Matplotlib itself.\nViewing content in this manner is not much different than reading\na hardbound textbook. To get the full benefit of Jupyter Books you\ncan run, and even modify, the example code in real time! This\ninteraction allows you to experiment with different parameters and\nobserve instantly how results change.","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"cZHCDeAtI2"}],"key":"xzQLOqfiUH"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":63,"column":1},"end":{"line":64,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"There are two ways that you can execute the Pythia Foundations book\nchapters. Both are described below.","position":{"start":{"line":63,"column":1},"end":{"line":63,"column":1}},"key":"c9SyrQYRIS"}],"key":"hF0nNZ801X"},{"type":"image","url":"/_preview/582/build/foundations_diagram-a705179e83277767f7a5f05d623083c6.png","alt":"Annotated Pythia Foundations home page","position":{"start":{"line":66,"column":1},"end":{"line":66,"column":1}},"key":"r75fHhrWba","urlSource":"../images/foundations_diagram.png"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":68,"column":1},"end":{"line":68,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Interacting with Jupyter Notebooks in the cloud via Binder","position":{"start":{"line":68,"column":1},"end":{"line":68,"column":1}},"key":"hGJZixNHRc"}],"identifier":"interacting-with-jupyter-notebooks-in-the-cloud-via-binder","label":"Interacting with Jupyter Notebooks in the cloud via Binder","html_id":"interacting-with-jupyter-notebooks-in-the-cloud-via-binder","implicit":true,"key":"i8UdoV2Zig"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":84,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The simplest way to interact with a Jupyter Notebook is through\n","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"kJIdWCD968"},{"type":"link","url":"https://binder.projectpythia.org","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Binder","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"bUsTOJhpzj"}],"urlSource":"https://binder.projectpythia.org","key":"pjbJ2cOazm"},{"type":"text","value":", which enables the execution of a\nJupyter Notebook in the cloud. The details of how this works are not\nimportant for now. All you need to know is how to launch a Pythia\nFoundations book chapter via Binder. Simply navigate your mouse to\nthe top right corner of the book chapter you are viewing and click\non the rocket ship icon (see the screenshot above), and a text box will appear.\nType or paste the Pythia Binder link (","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"VNhUiHotg3"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"https://binder.projectpythia.org","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"DSnY1JWKO6"},{"type":"text","value":") and click “Launch”.\nAfter a moment you should be presented with a\nnotebook that you can interact with. You’ll be able to execute code\nand even change the example programs. At first the code cells\nhave no output, until you execute them by pressing\n","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"R3H1voz7LX"},{"type":"keyboard","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Shift","key":"Mmf6w5PR9U"}],"key":"XZFxuyzs1L"},{"type":"text","value":"+","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"VhNxrvrRXI"},{"type":"keyboard","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Enter","key":"mzUlIpp4Fx"}],"key":"INR7fFsUSe"},{"type":"text","value":". Complete details on how to interact with\na live Jupyter notebook are described in ","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"HtdTj3VMBK"},{"type":"link","url":"https://foundations.projectpythia.org/foundations/getting-started-jupyter","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Getting Started with\nJupyter","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"iDWNfGhxGE"}],"urlSource":"https://foundations.projectpythia.org/foundations/getting-started-jupyter","key":"pu3s0NjXge"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"cylohoPE1o"}],"key":"fiZkJShfIZ"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Interacting with Jupyter Books locally","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"key":"BmGfi3LrAT"}],"identifier":"interacting-with-jupyter-books-locally","label":"Interacting with Jupyter Books locally","html_id":"interacting-with-jupyter-books-locally","implicit":true,"key":"KxyeAID1Mt"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":93,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Sometimes it may make more sense to download a book chapter and run\nit on your local laptop or PC. Perhaps you want to co-opt a notebook\nfor your own purposes, or load your own local data. Downloading an\nindividual chapter is trivial: click on the download icon, also\nlocated in the top right corner of the book chapter you are viewing,\nand click on the filename that appears.","position":{"start":{"line":88,"column":1},"end":{"line":88,"column":1}},"key":"FZco7QIp7a"}],"key":"Oih6STzsJK"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":95,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"That was the easy part. Getting the notebook to execute locally may\ntake a little more work. The book was created to run in a particular\nPython environment, managed with Conda. If you don’t have a up-to-date\nversion of Conda on your machine, you’ll want to install one. A brief\nintroduction to installing Conda is available ","position":{"start":{"line":95,"column":1},"end":{"line":95,"column":1}},"key":"i6C8EqoVxX"},{"type":"link","url":"https://foundations.projectpythia.org/foundations/conda","position":{"start":{"line":95,"column":1},"end":{"line":95,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"here","position":{"start":{"line":95,"column":1},"end":{"line":95,"column":1}},"key":"yFnNpNlQKT"}],"urlSource":"https://foundations.projectpythia.org/foundations/conda","key":"Sl0B6cykct"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":95,"column":1},"end":{"line":95,"column":1}},"key":"L7z8cUjtmi"}],"key":"eI8qp9EBXp"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":104,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Once you’ve installed Conda you will need to create and activate a Conda environment\nthat is compatible with Pythia Foundation’s notebooks. This\ncan be done with two commands from the terminal, one to create the\nenvironment and one to activate it:","position":{"start":{"line":101,"column":1},"end":{"line":101,"column":1}},"key":"mogDh9Zgnb"}],"key":"f0GkKgBv44"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"conda env create --yes -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ProjectPythia/pythia-foundations/main/environment.yml\nconda activate pythia-book-dev","position":{"start":{"line":106,"column":1},"end":{"line":109,"column":1}},"key":"XofdP0XC9k"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":117,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"You should only need to create the environment once (run the first\ncommand above). But if you download another notebook later, you will\nneed to activate ","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"ohEAkLPRoU"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"pythia-book-dev","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"awMv035NaO"}],"key":"HtO9NVCPnl"},{"type":"text","value":" if\nit is not currently active, for example if you open up a new\nterminal window, or deactivate ","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"iBJ0O6aPy2"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"pythia-book-dev","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"jQHVZJ8Fna"}],"key":"TITY9WW1P0"},{"type":"text","value":" explicitly with\nthe ","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"KTMAuFdQ5q"},{"type":"inlineCode","value":"conda","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"A0EHHDM7Qq"},{"type":"text","value":" command. Again, more information on Conda can be\nfound ","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"uJob4pAo7i"},{"type":"link","url":"https://foundations.projectpythia.org/foundations/conda","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"here","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"KthRQeJzmp"}],"urlSource":"https://foundations.projectpythia.org/foundations/conda","key":"GGLNuo59sY"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"YITBRz1Emo"}],"key":"ozZAaptVA6"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":119,"column":1},"end":{"line":123,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Now that your ","position":{"start":{"line":119,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"key":"TVVLX0HByO"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":119,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"pythia-book-dev","position":{"start":{"line":119,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"key":"fr1redKhbs"}],"key":"SyZqO8e3Ws"},{"type":"text","value":" environment is activated,\nchange your working directory to the\nlocation where you downloaded the notebook (.ipynb file) and start\nthe Jupyter Notebook server. For example if you downloaded the\nnotebook file to your home directory you would do:","position":{"start":{"line":119,"column":1},"end":{"line":119,"column":1}},"key":"xrT2U7OLvY"}],"key":"s6wr32OGgI"},{"type":"code","lang":"","value":"cd ~\njupyter lab","position":{"start":{"line":125,"column":1},"end":{"line":128,"column":1}},"key":"WYgt3FMgT2"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":130,"column":1},"end":{"line":139,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A local Jupyter Notebook server should open in your web browser.\nSimply open the .ipynb file using the Notebook server’s file browser\nand you are good to go. If you want to work with many Pythia Foundations\nnotebooks, you might want to “clone the site”\nand download all of the notebooks. First, click on the GitHub icon (see the screenshot above)\nto open the Pythia Foundations GitHub repository.\nThen follow the instructions in our Getting Started with GitHub\n","position":{"start":{"line":130,"column":1},"end":{"line":130,"column":1}},"key":"fVsn8qU5pm"},{"type":"link","url":"https://foundations.projectpythia.org/foundations/getting-started-github","position":{"start":{"line":130,"column":1},"end":{"line":130,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"guide","position":{"start":{"line":130,"column":1},"end":{"line":130,"column":1}},"key":"v5ZE1id5md"}],"urlSource":"https://foundations.projectpythia.org/foundations/getting-started-github","key":"cZOwipBq5L"},{"type":"text","value":"\nfor cloning a repository. The steps used above for configuring your\nConda environment should work for this method as well.","position":{"start":{"line":130,"column":1},"end":{"line":130,"column":1}},"key":"OAnao45cUH"}],"key":"uL3epB1Lq3"}],"key":"dhvMPRfrVv"}],"key":"AdlRDEmc2L"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Pythia Foundations","url":"/","group":"Pythia Foundations"},"next":{"title":"How to Cite This Book","url":"/preamble/how-to-cite","group":"Preamble"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3000"}